Dependency injection in .NET 7 can be implemented using the built-in dependency injection framework or by using a third-party library such as Autofac or Ninject.

To use the built-in dependency injection framework, you will need to:

1. Register the services you want to inject as dependencies in the ConfigureServices method of the Startup class.
2. Use the [Service] attribute on the constructor of the class that needs the dependency.
3. Use the [Activate] attribute on the constructor of the class that needs the dependency.

For example:


```
public void ConfigureServices(IServiceCollection services)
{
 services.AddTransient<IMyService, MyService>();
}

[Activate]
public class MyClass
{
 private readonly IMyService _myService;

 public MyClass(IMyService myService)
 {
 _myService = myService;
 }
}
```
You can also use third-party libraries such as Autofac or Ninject to achieve the same.

In general, you will need to:

1. Install the library using NuGet
2. Register the services you want to inject as dependencies
3. Use the library's container to resolve dependencies in the constructor of the class that needs them.

Example with Autofac


```
var builder = new ContainerBuilder();
builder.RegisterType<MyService>().As<IMyService>();
var container = builder.Build();
```
Example with Ninject


```
var kernel = new StandardKernel();
kernel.Bind<IMyService>().To<MyService>();
```
In both the examples above, you can see that you are binding the interface "IMyService" to a concrete implementation "MyService".

There are a couple of ways to make the dependency injection mapping dynamic for mocking and testing purposes:

1. Using a configuration file: You can use a configuration file (e.g. JSON or XML) to specify the mapping between interfaces and concrete implementations. This way, you can change the mapping easily without modifying the code.
2. Using a factory pattern: You can create a factory class that is responsible for creating the concrete implementations based on the interface. This factory class can be easily replaced with a mock implementation for testing.
3. Using runtime configuration: You can use a runtime configuration, this allows you to change the implementation of an interface at runtime. This is typically used in conjunction with a container such as Autofac or Ninject.
4. Using Service Provider: You can use the built-in .NET Core service provider to register and resolve dependencies at runtime. This allows you to replace the implementation of a service with a mock implementation for testing.

An example of using runtime configuration with Autofac:


```
var builder = new ContainerBuilder();
builder.RegisterType<MyService>().As<IMyService>();
builder.RegisterType<MyTestService>().As<IMyService>().Named<IMyService>("Test");
var container = builder.Build();

// Resolve the "MyService" implementation
var myService = container.Resolve<IMyService>();

// Resolve the "MyTestService" implementation
var myTestService = container.ResolveNamed<IMyService>("Test");
```
In this example, you can see that you are using the "Named" method to register the "MyTestService" implementation under the name "Test". This allows you to resolve the "MyTestService" implementation by using the "ResolveNamed" method and passing the name "Test".

You can also use the IServiceProvider to register and resolve dependencies at runtime.


```
services.AddTransient<IMyService, MyService>();

...

var serviceProvider = services.BuildServiceProvider();
var myService = serviceProvider.GetService<IMyService>();
```
You can use the above methods to achieve dynamic dependency injection mapping, which will enable you to easily switch between different implementations of a service for testing and other purposes.

