Autofac provides the ability to tag an instance with a specific key, so that you can create different scopes with different instances of the same service.

You can use the `WithTag` method to tag an instance, and then use the `BeginLifetimeScope` method to create a new scope with a specific tag.

Here's an example of how you can use tagging to create different scopes with different instances of the same service:


```
// Register the services
var builder = new ContainerBuilder();
builder.RegisterType<MyService>().As<IMyService>().InstancePerLifetimeScope().WithTag("Tag1");
builder.RegisterType<MyService>().As<IMyService>().InstancePerLifetimeScope().WithTag("Tag2");

// Build the container
var container = builder.Build();

// Create a new scope with Tag1
using (var scope1 = container.BeginLifetimeScope("Tag1"))
{
 var myService1 = scope1.Resolve<IMyService>();
 // Use myService1
}

// Create a new scope with Tag2
using (var scope2 = container.BeginLifetimeScope("Tag2"))
{
 var myService2 = scope2.Resolve<IMyService>();
 // Use myService2
}
```
In this example, you can see that you are registering the service `MyService` twice, one with tag "Tag1" and one with tag "Tag2" and both have the same lifetime "InstancePerLifetimeScope".

Then, you are creating two new scopes, one with tag "Tag1" and another with tag "Tag2" by using the `BeginLifetimeScope` method and passing the corresponding tag as a parameter.

Finally, you are resolving the instances `myService1` and `myService2` within the scopes, and using them as needed. `myService1` is resolved within the scope with tag "Tag1" and `myService2` within the scope with tag "Tag2".

It's important to notice that, when the scopes are disposed, all instances created within them will also be disposed, so you should ensure that you're keeping the instances that you still need, before disposing the scopes.

In summary, Autofac provides the ability to tag an instance with a specific key, so that you can create different scopes with different instances of the same service, by using the `WithTag` method to tag an instance and then use the `BeginLifetimeScope` method to create a new scope with a specific tag.

The `WithTag` method and the `InstancePerMatchingLifetimeScope` method in Autofac are similar in that they both allow you to create different instances of the same service within different scopes. But they are used in slightly different ways.

The `WithTag` method is used to tag an instance of a service with a specific key, when you register the service. Then, you can use the `BeginLifetimeScope` method to create a new scope with a specific tag, and use the `Resolve` method to resolve an instance of the service within that scope.


