In summary, the `WithTag` method is used to tag an instance of a service with a specific key when you register the service, and then use the `BeginLifetimeScope` method to create a new scope with a specific tag and use the `Resolve` method to resolve an instance of the service within that scope. `InstancePerMatchingLifetimeScope` is used to create different instances of the same service within different scopes based on a matching tag or key, that you can specify when you register the service, and then use the `Resolve` method to resolve an instance of the service within a specific scope.

When you use the `WithTag` method to tag an instance of a service with a specific key, and then create a new scope with a different tag using the `BeginLifetimeScope` method, Autofac will not be able to find any service instances that match the tag of the new scope, so it will throw an `DependencyResolutionException`.

For example, if you have registered a service `MyService` with tag "Tag1" using the `WithTag` method, and then you create a new scope with tag "Tag2" using the `BeginLifetimeScope` method like this:


```
var builder = new ContainerBuilder();
builder.RegisterType<MyService>().As<IMyService>().InstancePerLifetimeScope().WithTag("Tag1");
var container = builder.Build();
using (var scope = container.BeginLifetimeScope("Tag2"))
{
 var myService = scope.Resolve<IMyService>();
 //...
}
```
Autofac will not be able to find any service instances that match the tag "Tag2" because the service instances are tagged with "Tag1" and it will throw an `DependencyResolutionException` with a message like this: "No scope with a Tag matching 'Tag2' is visible from the scope in which the instance was requested."

It's worth mentioning that, when you use the `InstancePerMatchingLifetimeScope` method, the same thing will happen if you don't specify the tag of the scope when you create it or if the tag of the scope is different from the tag you specified when you registered the service.

