Lesson 3: Interfaces in TypeScript

In object-oriented programming, an interface is a contract that specifies the structure of an object. In TypeScript, you can use interfaces to define the structure of objects, classes, and other custom types.

For example, consider the following interface:


```typescript
interface User {
 name: string;
 age: number;
}
```
This interface defines a `User` type with two properties: `name` and `age`. To implement this interface, you can create an object that conforms to its structure. For example:


```css
let user: User = {
 name: 'John Doe',
 age: 25
};
```
You can also use interfaces with classes. For example:


```typescript
interface User {
 name: string;
 age: number;
}

class Person implements User {
 name: string;
 age: number;

 constructor(name: string, age: number) {
 this.name = name;
 this.age = age;
 }
}

let person = new Person('John Doe', 25);
```
In this example, the `Person` class implements the `User` interface. This means that the class must have the same properties and structure as the interface.

Interfaces are a powerful feature in TypeScript that can help you write more maintainable and scalable code. They allow you to define the structure of objects and classes, and enforce that structure throughout your application.

